# Testing

`docs/COVERAGE.md` is the authoritative guidance for writing and reviewing
tests. Read it before adding or changing tests, and keep tests consistent with
it. Update `docs/COVERAGE.md` when the policy evolves.

## Core principles (see `docs/COVERAGE.md` for full detail)

- Test **real behavior**, not metrics. 100% should mean logic and error paths
  are genuinely exercised, never that hard branches were hidden.
- Use the **real `faiss` and `numpy`**; only fake the boundaries (embedding
  client, `get_settings`, `get_active_embedding_model`, DB session,
  `write_debug_file`).
- **Reset module-level global state between tests** with an autouse fixture so
  tests do not leak state.
- **Make background work deterministic** (replace `threading.Thread` with a
  synchronous stand-in or monkeypatch the scheduled function).
- Prefer **one assertion target per test** with a short comment naming the
  branch being exercised.
- Assert on `caplog` for best-effort failure / log branches.

## `# pragma: no cover`

Only pragma genuinely untestable code (defensive guards, re-export shims, truly
unreachable safety branches), and always add an inline comment justifying it.
Never pragma real business logic, parsing, retrieval/index assembly, or any
branch a caller can reach with valid input — write a test instead.

## Running coverage

From `backend/`, pass the config explicitly
(`--cov-config=../pyproject.toml`) or use `make coverage-backend`, otherwise the
`omit` list is not discovered.
